{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"99dbacc3-20d5-4c69-9fe8-cdaac99a9819","content":"Good news — with .NET 10 SDK, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft Testing Platform **by default**. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property was a .NET 9 opt-in bridge and is no longer needed.\n\nYou only need `EnableMSTestRunner` (which makes MSTest emit an MTP-based executable). I'll remove the obsolete property:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_s0jIpu1gLEKtop7Lkgbco1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-743d1b41725f4fca9a9093ee28c4e8ab/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>","new_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-743d1b41725f4fca9a9093ee28c4e8ab/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"35049a01-d0d6-408f-93af-ed00a931e1e6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"With .NET 10 SDK, `dotnet test` natively supports Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP) without the need for the `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property. That property was a bridge/opt-in for .NET 9 SDK to route `dotnet test` through MTP instead of VSTest. In .NET 10, MTP is the default test runner for `dotnet test`, so you can remove that property.\n\nThe `EnableMSTestRunner` property is still needed — it tells MSTest to produce an executable test host using MTP.\n\nLet me make the change.","outputTokens":418},"id":"3f6ef8b5-91d1-45b3-8256-0ce4c8b7d6c0","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:47:21.114Z","parentId":"b3769e02-0d53-42ec-aa26-53db5b0f2dba"}
